  "response": "Let me break down the answer into two parts:\n\nGreat Lakes Water Sources:\n1. Precipitation (rain and snow)\n2. Groundwater\n3. Rivers and streams that flow into the lakes\n4. Snowmelt from surrounding regions\n5. Small percentage from direct surface runoff\n\nThe water sources are primarily from the surrounding watershed, which includes parts of the United States and Canada.\n\nRegarding wildlife comparison with Lake Sevan:\nLake Sevan (in Armenia) and the Great Lakes have quite different ecosystems:\n\nGreat Lakes:\n- More diverse fish species\n- Include salmon, trout, walleye, perch\n- Multiple invasive species\n- Large biodiversity due to varied habitats\n\nLake Sevan:\n- Smaller ecosystem\n- Unique endemic fish species like Sevan trout\n- Less biodiversity\n- More vulnerable to environmental changes\n- Historically impacted by water level fluctuations\n\nWhile both are important freshwater ecosystems, the Great Lakes are significantly larger and more complex in terms of wildlife and ecological systems.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of these water systems?",
